article.description: Nykesha Sales scored 16 points and Elaine Powell added 13 as the Orlando Miracle snapped an eight-game road losing streak with a 71-69 victory over the winless Miami Sol on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Miami stumbles to fourth loss to start season
article.linkText: Miracle tip hapless Sol, end eight-game road skid
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- Nykesha Sales scored 16 points and Elaine Powell added 13 as the Orlando Miracle snapped an eight-game road losing streak with a 71-69 victory over the winless Miami Sol on Tuesday night. Orlando survived despite turning the ball over three times in the final 57 seconds, including one with 8.9 seconds remaining while trying to protect a two-point lead. After a deflection, Miami got the ball back with 1.4 seconds left, but Pollyanna Johns Kimbrough could not get a shot off before the horn sounded. "It definitely feels good to get a road win,'' Sales said. "We knew that Miami was struggling and we didn't want to be the team that let them get back in a rhythm.'' Taj McWilliams-Franklin had 11 points and Katie Douglas had a career-high 10 rebounds for Orlando (2-1), which snapped a three-game losing streak against the Sol. The Miracle's last road win was July 12, 2001, at Charlotte. Kimbrough led four Miami players in double figures with 16 points, a career-high. Only three teams in WNBA history have ever started a season with more consecutive losses than Miami (0-4) has this season. The four losses have come by a combined 15 points. "We certainly had another opportunity, but didn't do it,'' Sol coach Ron Rothstein said. "It's frustrating.'' Sheri Sam had 12 points and nine rebounds, but continued to struggle offensively for the Sol. She scored seven points in a 68-second span in the first half, but missed her next eight shots from the field and finished 4-for-13. Sandy Brondello added 12 points for Miami. Rookie forward Lindsey Yamasaki, who missed Miami's first three games with a high ankle sprain, made her WNBA debut and scored nine points in 27 minutes. Orlando outscored Miami 20-9 over the final 7:13 of the first half to tie it at 36. The Miracle made their last 11 shots before halftime. "We didn't take very good care of the basketball,'' Rothstein said. "We should have been up by 10 at the half.'' Orlando held Miami to 34 percent shooting in the second half. "The key was we just played defense. Defense is what wins on the road,'' Orlando coach Dee Brown said. "We've been scoring points, but we've been giving up entirely too many points. It's going to be defense that keeps us in games.''

Game notes
Tip-off was seven minutes behind schedule because several banks of halogen lamps were not working. ... Orlando never led by more than six points in the second half, but Miami couldn't come closer than within one. ... Miami has lost four straight home games, dating to last season.
